page.title: 13Natural History.
page.content: As Sywell is a country area it is fortunate in having a rich wild life. Small rodents, grey squirrels, foxes, rabbits, weasels, stoats, muntjac deer common frogs, toads, newts and even grass snakes can be seen or their tracks found. There is a very varied selection of birds. During a survey of bird visitors to the School bird table 14 different types were recorded: house sparrow, dunnock, robin, blue tit, great tit, starling, chaffinch, greenfinch, bull finch, blackbird, thrush, collared dove, wood pigeon, pied wagtail. Swallows are annual visitors to the Rectory Stables. Many other species can be seen in the farmland. A colony of bats uses the church as a roosting place (and cafeteria!) at the same season each year. Polythene sheets are necessary to cover the altar!
